The Cure are an English rock band formed in Crawley, West 
Sussex in 1976. The band has experienced several line-up 
changes, with frontman, vocalist, guitarist and principal 
songwriter Robert Smith being the only constant member. The 
Cure first began releasing music in the late 1970s with its 
debut album Three Imaginary Boys; this, along with several 
early singles, placed the band as part of the post-punk and 
new wave movements that had sprung up in the wake of the punk 
rock revolution in the United Kingdom. During the early 1980s
the band's increasingly dark and tormented music helped form 
the gothic rock genre.
